Defect Description: String should be printed in reverse order. String is parsed character by character in reverse order while string[i] character is printed. Conditional is initialized as (i=string.length() - 1, i $<$ string.length(), i--)
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: When parsing arrays or strings as arrays, the most common way is to parse from the start of the string or array to the end with the for loop conditional (i=0, i<string.length(), i++). When reverse parsing, i must be set to the length of the string or array – 1, with the conditional that i $>$= 0, and with i decrementing by 1.

Defect Description: Initially adopted a push model to run tests real time at the time the event was received. After increasing test volume, scheduling caused hotspots and oversaturation of test agent system resources resulting in test failures. Refactored to use of local queueing with N test worker services to evenly space testing and avoid overloading test agents.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The push model led to uneven resource consumption, with bursts of tests overwhelming test agents. As test volume increased, resource contention caused failures. The root cause was the lack of a controlled scheduling mechanism to distribute tests more evenly. The issue was resolved by implementing local queueing with worker services to regulate test execution.

Defect Description: While parsing through a string, each character should be checked to see if it matches a given character and if it is the given nth instance of that character in the string. If it is the correct instance of the correct character, the character ‘0’ should be printed, otherwise the original character should be printed. In the case where the character did not match and the case where the character matched the given character and instance the behavior was correct. The case where the character matched but the instance did not match was neglected.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: When reviewing the design of one’s own work, N conditions = 3 : character and instance matches, character matches and instance does not match, and character does not match. The conditions reviewed were the first and third scenario: n=2 $<$ N=3 conditions were reviewed.

Defect Description: When comparing Integers in Java, == was used instead of .equals, resulting in a false boolean value even when the numeric values of the Integers was the same.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I didn’t know that Java uses caching for Integer values between -128 and 127 and creates new references for Integers outside of that range. So comparing Integers withing that range with == will reference the same value and return true but using == between to equally numeric Integers outside that range will return false.

Defect Description: Initially for cost reasons, some EC2 test agents were IPv6 only. Later I updated all test agents to dual stack. However, automated unit testing in CI/CD pipeline included a validation of IPv6 only EC2 instances which no longer existed resulting in a build failure.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The CI/CD pipeline continued to check for IPv6-only instances even after all test agents were converted to dual stack. The test logic was not updated to reflect the infrastructure change, leading to failures in automated validation.

Defect Description: AWS Lambda functions intermittently failed to utilize new code following UpdateFunctionCode operation. After failed attempts with adding sleep intervals, discovered that Lambda code updates adhere to an eventually consistent update model, wherein new code is not guaranteed to be accessible immediately after an update. Refactored to leverage an API providing the update status.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The assumption that updated Lambda code would be immediately available led to failures when old versions continued executing. The initial workaround of inserting sleep intervals did not reliably resolve the issue. The root cause was eventually identified as AWS’s eventual consistency model for Lambda deployments, necessitating the use of an API to check update status before invoking the function.
Human Error Modes: Lack of Knowledge, Difficulties with exponential developments

Defect Description: EBS block volumes intermittently fail to fully attach to EC2 instances resulting in stuck volumes, failed tests, and occupied /dev/xvdN device alias (do not appear in OS while AWS control plane believes they are in use). Added more robust error handling (force detach and block device alias from future testing).
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The AWS control plane reported the volume as attached, but the OS did not recognize it, leading to failed tests and resource conflicts. This issue stems from inconsistencies between AWS’s internal state tracking and actual EC2 instance state. The problem was mitigated by implementing force-detach logic and preventing reuse of affected block device aliases in subsequent tests.

Defect Description: While waiting for AWS EFS volumes to transition to available status, excessive API polling requests resulted in 529 throttling errors (request limits are not well documented). Introduced sleep spacing between requests to work around.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The script repeatedly polled the AWS API without rate limiting, leading to excessive requests and API throttling (529 errors). AWS does not clearly document the request limits for this operation, leading to unexpected failures. The issue was resolved by introducing a delay between requests.
Human Error Modes: Lack of Knowledge, Difficulties with exponential developments

Defect Description: BigQuery SQL queries intermittently failed due to invalid characters in large multiline stdout / stderr output captured and stored during test execution that failed to escape properly in bash test scripts. Used base64 encoding and decoding to resolve.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: The test script failed to properly escape or sanitize special characters when capturing and storing stdout/stderr output. This led to malformed SQL queries when inserting the output into BigQuery, causing intermittent failures. The issue was resolved by encoding the output in base64 before storage and decoding it when needed.

Defect Description: RabbitMQ messages lost during high volume queueing operations. Issue due to lack of ConfirmSelect and WaitForConfirm acknowledgements when using HTTP API with curl
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: System failed to ensure message durability due to reliance on an (incorrect) assumption that messages sent via HTTP API would be durably queued. The absence of ConfirmSelect and WaitForConfirm led to silent message loss under high load conditions.

Defect Description:

remove all
items from a
list that
satisfied some
condition:
for (int i = 0; i <
list.length();
i++) {
var item = list[i]
if (item should
be removed) {
list.removeAt(i)
}
}
This code
doesn't work
correctly
because as
you remove
items, that
reduces the
length of the
list. But the
iterator variable
item i still
increments.
This leads to
items which
appear right
after a
removed item
to be skipped.
Consider the
following
variant of this
error:
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This is an
example of
applying a
strong but now
wrong rule.
Using a for
loop to iterate
through a list
like this is
common
practice and is
usually an
effective
solution for
doing
something to
each element
of a list. This
technique is
the strong rule.
However, in
this case it is
incorrect
because the
list changes
and becomes
smaller as you
iterate through
it. In this case,
it requires the
programmer to
give additional
thought to the
situation
beyond
traditional
utilization of a
for loop list
iterator.

introduced new c sharp files that would work with the existing Factory State Machine
logic, and also with a newly introduced Goal Oriented Action Planning model. When I
finished and attempted to load a test scene in Unity, some of my updated or new files
were not compiling.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
My sub-goals of ensuring every related script
functioned with the updated code were not all completed.

Defect Description:
For a web development project, I had an email field that should have shown

Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I had attempted to fix the issue before
encountering it, as my peers notified the class discord that a starter file had the wrong

Defect Description:

had some minor inconsistencies in a couple css files. My initial lack of knowledge for the

Defect Description:
In a text adventure game I coded for one of my honors classes, I thought I

on the first go around.

Defect Description:
When attempting to use WSL on my machine, I was receiving an error code
preventing Ubuntu from launching. I tried a million different troubleshooting techniques
suggested online, and ended up getting the main error resolved, but a new one popped up

Couldn’t classify causes because of lack of information. I had
been regularly interacting with my WSL every day and it just randomly seemed to get
corrupted.

Defect Description:
When attempting to use a license key on turbo tax, I received an error code
because I needed to be logged in on the account associated with it.

I went over everything in my head before trying the
license key, and determined that I was good to go. Once I saw the error, my mind almost
immediately went to me not being logged in with the correct account.

Defect Description: For a web development project, I placed my api key in the wrong location.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I was confused and mistakenly grabbed the
wrong key for where the api key should have gone.

Defect Description:
When setting up a permissions management system on a local MC server
that I created, I had the wrong preference selected for modifying groups locally
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I had set up many permissions config
files for previous servers and assumed the new plugin I chose would behave the same
way as others I had used.

Defect Description:
When pulling logs from my work tablet, I needed to cross-check Mixpanel
to ensure that the correct names of events were being triggered on Mixpanel as well asthe correct number. I saw no events on Mixpanel after triggering the events on the tablet
and pulling the logs.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I was interrupted by having to deal
with an incoming zoom call during the process, which caused me to forget to connect to
the correct network on the tablet

Defect Description:
For a web development project, I was following a local database(MongoDB)
setup tutorial from a groupmate for our project. When setting up the .env file inside the
server directory, the expected Port was not working.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
As this was my first time setting up MongoDB
on my PC, I was confused and swapped two ports on the instructions in my head. Once I
switched the field to the correct port everything worked fine.

Defect Description: Entered step instead of stepi
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
During my “bomb” assignment for CSCI 247, I had to be careful not to blow up my bomb by
going too far in the instructions while using the debugger. To do this, I used the command
“stepi,” which allowed me to go forward one step in assembly. This should not be confused with
“step”, which goes forward one C instruction, which is a lot further than I wanted to test.
Unfortunately, since they look similar, I experienced perceptual confusion and entered step as a
command, which ended up blowing up my bomb.

Defect Description: Used space in terminal which enters last command out of habit, crashing my program
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
During that same bomb assignment, I figured out that when simply pressing enter the previous
command is used, which is quite efficient when doing the same step over and over again. After
using this a lot, I went back to pen and paper, devising a strategy before trying again. When
trying again, I entered “continue” in gdb to go to my breakpoint, and although I should have
typed “stepi” to go to the next step and then continued to use it via the enter key, I immediately
pressed enter out of habit, intending to go forward one step but instead using continue which,
since I had not more breakpoints set, blew up the bomb. This is an example of
strong-but-now-wrong: I was so used to enter going forward one line of code that I expected it to
do the same even when the previous command was not stepi.

Defect Description: Did not fully follow all cases when reimplementing a function in a bugged program
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While fixing a bug in a program given to me in a lab, I noticed an incorrect usage of unsigned
integers which created overflows. To fix this, I deleted the entire implementation, creating a
while loop which would prevent overflow. However, I failed to realize that the initial for loop I
deleted on its first cycle would print differently than on the other cycles, and this caused my
program to give unexpected results, failing the tests. I believe this to be an example of a
post-completion error, since I first needed to fix the overflow (step A), and then reimplement the
special case handling on the first iteration (step B), and since step B is not necessary to
completing step A and immediately follows it, I forgot to do it.

Defect Description: Error while working with hexadecimal values
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While working on an assignment using hexadecimal values, I was meant to choose the max
value. While working this out in my head, I first chose by the tens digits, and then when I saw a
9 in the one's digit I assumed that the number would be the greatest, regardless of what any of
the other numbers had in the one's digit, since this would be the case if I were working in
standard decimal format. This was me committing a strong-but-now-wrong error since in
hexadecimal 9 is not the greatest value, F is. It turns out, there was a value with an A in the
ones digit, which is greater than 9 meaning I was incorrect, and this caused me quite a bit of
confusion when my code disagreed with me.

Defect Description: Printed “-” rather than spaces in Magic Trees problem
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
In the magic trees problem assigned to us in class, I did not replace the “-” characters with
spaces, as required in the specification. This is a post-completion error, as the instruction to
replace those characters was the last line in the spec, and was not a necessary condition to
complete the task before it, which was more important to the actual functionality of the program.
Most likely, my brain got tired of reading and I skipped to looking at the example diagrams, not
realizing I was missing a step.

Defect Description: Did not sort correctly in LeetCode problem
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While solving a LeetCode problem where I was asked to sort items by the frequency of said
items. Then, the instructions said that if multiple values had the same frequency, that I should
sort them by decreasing order. However, since this was the last step, and was not necessary to
the task before, I forgot to do so, committing a post-completion error, and was surprised when
my result was not accepted.

Defect Description: Used undefined data type in C
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While coding in C, I used the data type “bool,” and was surprised when I got an error message
that the type “bool” was undefined. After looking it up, I found out that earlier version of C did not
have that data type, and that I could either use an integer or define it at the top of the file. This
error happened because I was told that booleans are in C and use the name bool, and therefore
updated my C schema, not realizing that this was only true for certain versions of C, and that
this was not true in the version I was using. This leads me to believe the cause of my error was
a rule-encoding deficiency.

Defect Description: Forgot to compile file after making changes
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While working on an assignment, I had to frequently make updates to a file, which would
thereafter have to be compiled. At one point, after making a change, I forgot to compile, which
meant I was not seeing my changes incorporated, which took me a minute to understand while
debugging. This is an example of a post-completion error, as it was the last step in the
sequence required to edit the file, and it was not required to complete the main task of editing
the file, which is what my brain was focused on, taking up the majority of my attention.

Defect Description: Personal project briefly broke due to issues with HTML tags
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
A user of one of my personal projects notified me that it was no longer working. Upon closer
inspection, I discovered it had broken across all platforms. The issue was rooted in how I was
identifying elements to edit on webpages: I grabbed them by their HTML tags, hoping that they
would not be changed during updates to the website. But evidently they did, and it is an
example of an error causing a fault that did not immediately lead to a failure. The error itself is in
my opinion an example of a lack of knowledge: I did not know how permanent the HTML tags
were, and if they would be changed or not by updates, as I have no knowledge of the eternal
workings of the websites I am creating extensions for in my personal project.

Defect Description: Distracted by working on too many separate functions
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
While doing a class assignment in a brand new topic, I started trying multiple things to test out
the functionality of what I was learning (buffer overflow attacks). When I came back I started toflesh out one of these things and was surprised when I was getting unexpected outputs. I
eventually realized that my unfinished framework from earlier was breaking things down the line,
as it was never meant to be finalized. This is an example of an omission following an
interruption: the time I took away from the computer caused me to forget that there were other
aspects of the attack that were unfinished, and so I omitted the lines that would have caused the
program to run correctly.

Defect Description:
The first example is an error I made on an assignment where I was to compare a list of
runtimes and sort them in order from least (fastest) to greatest (slowest). The submission was to
be a pdf constructed using LaTex. I mistakenly used greater than or equal to symbol ( ? ) instead
of the correct greater than symbol ( < ).
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred during the coding and review
stage because I used the wrong symbol when writing the LaTex code and failed to recognize my
mistake when reviewing my answers in the pdf output and at the skill-based performance level. I
am highly confident that this error was the result of Perceptual confusion. ? looks very similar to
< so used it instead.

Defect Description:
The second example is an error I made on an assignment where I was to create a function
that takes in an array of items in a set and an array of relations in a set and determines if the set is
transitive. Return true if it is false if it’s not. The assignment description gave a few examples of
correct and incorrect inputs but didn’t show any examples of edge cases. I forgot to include the
null set edge case leading to the function returning false instead of true.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred
during the coding stage and at the knowledge-based performance level. I am highly confident
that this error was the result of Bias Review. The instructions only contained examples of true
and false sets so I focused on getting those to work. Once they returned the proper values for all
of the sets I assumed I had successfully covered all the cases which led to me skipping over the
null set edge case.

Defect Description:
Another example is I was working on a homework assignment with multiple problems.
The instructions stated to solve the following problem, how we were to format our answers,
when the assignments was due, and at the end to write on the top of our paper if we worked
alone or with a team. I forgot to put that I worked alone on the top and as a result lost a
significant amount of points on the assignment.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred at the requirement level as
I skipped a requirement and at the review level as I was focused on reviewing the answers to thequestions. I am highly confident this is a Post-Completion Error. Writing if I worked alone was
the last step and it was smaller and nonessential to the main task of completing the homework.

Defect Description:
Another error I personally made is on a quiz the question was “to write down a
recurrence that computes a^n using divide and conquer. For example, if we are trying to compute
28, our algorithm should first compute b=24 and then return b*b. Be sure to include cases for
both odd and even n.” I incremented n by -2 each recursion instead of n/2.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred
at the coding stage as it was when I was actually writing the code that this occurred. This quiz
was timed so I did not have time to review my code. I have a medium level of confidence this
occurred at the knowledge-based level and is a Selectivity error. I missed the logically important
information that I was supposed to use divide and conquer because I was focused on including
both odd and even cases.

Defect Description:
The final error I personally made that I can remember for purposes of this project
occurred when I was trying to give a runtime analysis of a program similar to binary search. I
recognized it was similar to binary search and assumed the runtime was O(n log n), the runtimeof binary search. I focused on proving the runtime was O(n log n) instead of computing it from
scratch which resulted in me getting the wrong runtime.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred at the design
stage as I assumed the solution instead of working to find the best solution. I am highly confident
that this occurred at the knowledge-based level and is Confirmation Bias. I was trying to confirm
the solution and only focusing on the psychologically stagnant information that supported that
instead of the logically important information I needed to calculate the correct runtime.

Defect Description:
The first example is from a Student who was modifying a Radix sort algorithm to sort
negative numbers as well as positive numbers. The student updated all functions in Radix sort
but it still wasn’t working correctly. This was because they had forgotten to add a way to separate
the negative numbers from the positive numbers so the array of negative numbers was empty and
all values were in the positive numbers array.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This occurred at the coding stage and I believe at
the skill-based level. I am highly confident this is a Post-Completion Error as it was the smaller
final step in the larger task of updating the Radix sort algorithm.

Defect Description:
The second example is from a Student who was working on the 247 pointer lab. The first
portion of this lab is following step by step instructions provided by the teacher. This student was
talking to a friend who was working on the same project and as a result skipped over a step
causing the code to fail to compile.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This occurred at the coding stage and at the skill-based level.
I am highly confident this is an Omission Following Interruption as the student picked up the
instructions a step ahead after talking to their friend (interruption). I think this could also be
Perceptual Confusion as their friend was working on the same project and a few steps ahead so
it’s possible they were looking at their friend's code and mistook it for theirs causing them to
believe they were further along than they were.

Defect Description:
Another example is a Student was working on a Python truth table of XOR function in
141. The User inputs two true or false values in the form T or F and a boolean value that is the
result of XORing the inputs is returned. The Student used T or F instead of true or false forBoolean values causing a compile error as they were returning a char when the program expected
a boolean.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This occurred at the coding stage and the knowledge-based and skill-based levels.
This could be a Lack of Knowledge Error as the student hadn’t previously used boolean types so
didn’t know to use the keywords “true” and “false”. This could also be Perceptual Confusion as
the input is a char T or F which has the same function in this project as true or false resulting in
the student using the wrong one.

Defect Description:
A 145 assignment asked students to create an array of integers with length size. This
resulted in approximately 3-4 students students attempting to create new array in the way new
instances of an object are created after learning about objects the previous week. They wrote
Array a= new Array(int); instead of: int [] a = new int [size];.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This occurred at the coding stage
and at the rule-based level. I believe with medium confidence this is a “Strong-but-now-wrong”
Rule. Students were familiar with the creation of objects and had successfully used it multiple
times in the previous week so when faced with the new rule of creating arrays they mistakenly
used the familiar rule of creating objects.

Defect Description:
approximately 10-12
students used getters and setters instead of constructors like directed.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
This occurred at the design
and coding stage as the initial design lacked constructors and they wrote code for just getters and
setters instead. I believe with medium confidence this occurs at the rule-based level and is a
“Strong-but-now-wrong” Rule. The stronger rule of creating getters and setters to access private
variables was used instead of the newer rule of usinging constructors and setting the private
variables with input from the constructor arguments.

Defect Description:
The second error was using inheritance
instead of encapsulation to rewrite the class; around 20-25 students did this (possibly more I
should’ve counted exactly but it was a lot).
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis:
I believe this occurred at the requirements and design
stage because the code varied but the key concept stayed the same. I am highly confident this is
at the knowledge-based level and a Lack of Knowledge of what encapsulation is. It also could be
Selectivity and the students focused on the phycologically stagnant object-oriented part instead
of the logically important encapsulation part.

Defect Description: A project to create a program to perform bisection on a function must produce a table where results have 7 decimal places. My program would print with anywhere from 0 - 8
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I was not able to get the program to print the correct number of decimals, I solved the issue by changing the values to a string. Then using a method to specify a length of a string to get the desired decimal places

Defect Description: In my first time using matlab working with many polynomials many exponents are required. Using “^” is usually all that is required for this but matlab needs the syntax “.^”
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I used my experience from previous coding languages and applied to matlab where the rule is different

Defect Description: Deadwood is board game that was being made into a videogame version for assignment. This error was the player icons were obscuring the information of the location they were
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: While not technically required for the game to function the clutter in the ui caused by this made the game less fun to play. Solved by shrinking the player icon when they are in a place with information that could be covered

Defect Description: Related to 7 decimal places error. Data type for results was double when it matlab if you only need 7 decimal places the proper data type to use is single
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: This being my first project in matlab I was not familiar with the nuances of the variable types in language

Defect Description: In a program meant to perform bisection on a given function, the function I entered has a negative where there should have been a positive
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I mistakenly turned a positive integer into a negative one, unsure if it was a typo or a lapse. I did not catch error because the bisection was performed and the results were correct, I did not think to make sure the input was correct too .

Defect Description: for a newton's method program in matlab natural log is needed to calculate error. I had assumed ln would be syntax to use but matlab takes log as the natural log so there is no need for ln
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: Used the common syntax for math inputs not knowing that matlab has a different syntax.

Defect Description:
while loop in my newton's method program ran up to 1 times less than I had wanted. The goal is to produce an answer under a certain point such as 
(10)^-8. The while loop was set to > meaning the loop would stop when the answer got close enough or was equal to point, when it must be less than
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I was not considering the possibility of both sides being equal or close enough that the data type would see them as the same. (These are very small decimals with lots of zeros)

Defect Description: Bisection method in matlab should check the input to make sure that it is valid. If not it ends the program. I created this part first, made sure it worked then created the rest.
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: After making the rest of the program I only caught the error after putting the wrong input in. The program would give me the error message then attempt to perform the function anyway. I added a return statement to create the break

Defect Description: I needed to make a graph for a specific function and mark the a specific point on the graphs. Matlab was showing a series of points instead, placing multiple points on the y-axis in a line on the x-point I selected
Error-Prone Scenario Analysis: I tried to input the points as part of the graph but because the graph is dependent on input values it would put the point on the graph for multiple variations of the line. I solved this be creating a separate individual point and placing it onto the graph.
